{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Anne-Marie Imafidon | honorific_suffix = [[MBE]] | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = Anne-Marie_Imafidon,_Bojana_Bellamy_2018.jpg | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = Photo of Anne-Marie Imafidon | caption = Anne-Marie Imafidon in 2018 | birth_date = 1990 | birth_place = England | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = {{plainlist | * Mathematics * Computer science * Social enterprise }} | workplaces = {{plainlist | * [[Stemettes]] }} | patrons = | education = [[Oxford University]] | thesis_title = <!--(or | thesis1_title = and | thesis2_title = )--> | thesis_url = <!--(or | thesis1_url = and | thesis2_url = )--> | thesis_year = <!--(or | thesis1_year = and | thesis2_year = )--> | doctoral_advisor = <!--(or | doctoral_advisors = )--> | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = {{plainlist | * Academic child prodigy }} | influences = | influenced = | awards = [[MBE]] (2016) }}
'''Anne-Marie Osawemwenze Ore-Ofe Imafidon''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/580999/new-years-honours-2017-full-list.pdf|format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]|date=30 December 2016|accessdate=31 December 2016|work=[[Gov.uk]]|publisher=[[Government Digital Service]]|title=New Year's Honours list 2017|page=66}}</ref> (born 1990) is a British computing, mathematics and language [[child prodigy]].<ref name="Child Prodigy">{{cite news|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/TA-Mar-9-wacky_7469110|title=Wacky TEENs|date=9 March 2010|work=Jamaica Observer|publisher=Jamaica Observer|page=1|accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref> She is one of the youngest to pass two [[GCSE]]s in two different subjects while in primary school. She passed two GCSE Examinations (in Mathematics and Information technology) at the age of 11.<ref name="A Level">{{cite news|url=http://newsrss.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/1494503.stm|title=A-level for 11 year old|date=16 August 2001|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|page=1|accessdate=28 August 2010}}</ref> Imafidon founded and became CEO of [[Stemettes]] in 2013, a social enterprise promoting women in [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] careers, and was honoured with an [[MBE]] in 2016.<ref name="Honours List">{{cite web|title=New Year's Honours list 2017 - GOV.UK|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/new-years-honours-list-2017|website=www.gov.uk|publisher=Government of the UK|accessdate=21 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Imafidon was born in England in 1990. Her father, Chris Imafidon, is an [[ophthalmologist]] who emigrated to London, and her mother is Ann Imafidon.<ref name="Black America Web 2013">{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Erica|title=Little Known Black History Fact: The Smartest Family in Britain|url=https://blackamericaweb.com/2013/03/11/little-known-black-history-fact-the-smartest-family-in-britain/|accessdate=21 May 2017|work=Black America Web|publisher=Interactive One|date=12 March 2013}}</ref> She and her 3 younger siblings, Christina and twins Peter and Paula, are child prodigies, breaking age records in educational attainments.<ref name="Black America Web 2013" />
Imafidon began school at St Saviour Church of England Primary School in Walthamstow, London,<ref name="Black America Web 2013" /> and could speak six languages by the age of 10.<ref name="Atlanta Black Star">{{cite news|last1=Staff|first1=A. B. S.|title=Former Child Prodigy Anne-Marie Imafidon Changing The World With Stemettes|url=http://atlantablackstar.com/2013/10/21/former-child-prodigy-anne-marie-imafidon-changing-world-stemettes/|accessdate=21 May 2017|work=Atlanta Black Star|date=21 October 2013}}</ref>
At 13, in 2003, she received a British scholarship to study mathematics at [[Johns Hopkins University]].<ref name="Rebecca Smithers">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/aug/15/schools.alevels2003|title=IT success for boy aged 12|last=Smithers|first=Rebecca|date=15 August 2003|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media|page=1|accessdate=28 August 2010}}</ref> At 15, in 2005, she was admitted a degree program by the [[University of Oxford]]. At 17, she started a master's degree at Oxford University and, at 19 in June 2010, she became the youngest ever graduate with a master's degree.<ref>[http://yegs.org/yegs-hall-of-fame-anne-marie-imafidon-1990/ Anne-Marie Imafidon profile at yegs.org]; accessed 6 July 2011</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Raton |first=Taki S. |title=Prodigy is youngest to receive Masters’ Degree from Oxford|url=http://milwaukeecourieronline.com/index.php/2012/05/03/prodigy-is-youngest-to-receive-masters-degree-from-oxford/|work=Milwaukee Courier |date=3 May 2012 }}</ref>
==Career== Imafidon worked briefly for [[Goldman Sachs]], [[Hewlett Packard]], and [[Deutschebank]] before launching and becoming CEO of [[Stemettes]] in 2013, championing the work of women in STEM.<ref name="Stemettes - MBE announcement">{{cite web|title=Stemettes Co-Founder awarded MBE in New Years Honours - Stemettes|url=http://stemettes.org/blog/2016/12/30/stemettes-co-founder-awarded-mbe-in-new-years-honours/|website=Stemettes|accessdate=21 May 2017|date=30 December 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://stemettes.org/ Stemettes.org]</ref> Stemettes runs panel sessions and hackathons supporting girls and young women who are considering a STEM career. In April 2014, Imafidon was the keynote speaker at the [[BCSWomen]] Lovelace Colloquium<ref>[http://www.computerweekly.com/blogs/witsend/2014/02/introducing-the-speakers-at-the-bcswomen-lovelace-colloquium-2014.html Introducing the Speakers at the BCSWomen Lovelace Colloquium on Computer Weekly]; accessed 19 April 2014]</ref>
==Honors== * BCS ([[British Computer Society]]) Young IT professional of the year, 2013.<ref name="BCS 2013">{{cite web|title=2013 Personal Excellence Awards {{!}} Winners and highly commended {{!}} 2013 Awards {{!}} IT Industry Awards Archive {{!}} UK IT Industry Awards {{!}} Awards and competitions {{!}} Events {{!}} BCS - The Chartered Institute for IT|url=http://www.bcs.org/content/ConWebDoc/51633|website=www.bcs.org|publisher=BCS|accessdate=21 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> * Red Magazine, Women of the Year award, 2014.<ref name="Red Magazine 2014">{{cite news|last1=Lunn|first1=Natasha|title=the women shaping your world|url=http://www.redonline.co.uk/red-women/red-women-of-the-year/red-women-of-the-year-awards-2014/winners-2014|accessdate=21 May 2017|work=www.redonline.co.uk|publisher=Red Magazine|date=3 September 2014|language=en}}</ref> * Prime Minister's Points of Light Award, 2014.<ref name="Points of Light Award 2014">{{cite web|title=Points of Light: October 2014 winners - GOV.UK|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/points-of-light-october-2014-winners|website=www.gov.uk|publisher=Government of the UK|accessdate=21 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> * MBE, 2016: "For services to young women within STEM careers".<ref name="Honours List" />
